body:
The watcher hot path is already O(appended bytes) via `readSessionFileIncremental` (byte offset + tail fingerprint + retained parse state). But that state lives only in memory: after an app restart, the cold-start scan does a **full read of every session JSONL** in the worker. For very large live transcripts (hundreds of MB) that makes startup indexing pay the whole file cost on every launch.

**Requirement:** persist the incremental parse state across restarts so the cold-start scan reads only the delta since the last run:

- store `{ offset, tail fingerprint, serialized parse state, metrics }` per session file (SQLite, next to the session cache row);
- on startup, verify the fingerprint exactly like the in-memory path does (shrink or tail mismatch â†’ full re-read, so stale state can never produce a wrong row);
- invalidation must be airtight â€” a wrong cache row is worse than a slow scan. Version the persisted state and drop it wholesale when the parser changes (e.g. keyed on a parser-schema constant bumped with any change to `applyEntryLine`/`buildSessionRow`).

Only worth doing if startup indexing is actually felt: measure first (log cold-scan duration + biggest file sizes), implement only if the numbers justify the invalidation complexity.
